  <span id="freeText13322955471462527755" style="display:none">What was I doing when I was 14? Certainly not enlisting the help of mean U.S. Marshal Rooster Cogburn and Texas Ranger LaBoeuf to hunt down my father’s killer through the mountains and wilderness of Arkansas. At that age, I had… gone camping… I guess. Put me in Mattie’s shoes, and I would’ve floundered somewhere between haggling for the repayment of a stolen saddle and crossing a river on a horse. But if we placed Mattie squarely in 2020, I have no doubt she’d be chasing down the tails of every unjust and lawless scoundrel who did her wrong. At this point, she’d probably have dismantled our entire executive branch and some senators to boot. <br /><br />In other words, Mattie Ross of near Dardanelle, Arkansas is the spunky, no-nonsense girl protagonist that I never knew I needed to have in literature. Charles Portis has made me fall wholly in love with Mattie’s unflinching, ascetic, deadpan narration. She writes as a whip-smart and unsentimental spinster, recounting events decades earlier that transpired in 1873—how she chased after Tom Chaney, that vile man who shot her kind father and dashed off into Indian territory to avoid retribution. He would of course come to rue that decision, for little did he know that Mattie was a level-headed girl of 14 who would gladly enact retribution. <br /><br />Society might’ve called her an “unnatural child” who refused to wait patiently for the law to get its hat on straight, but Mattie could care less that Tom Chaney be punished for “how many dogs and fat men he killed in Texas.” No, he would pay for killing her father. The most unadorned writing is veritably teeming with the vitality of Mattie’s personality, unhumorous in tone but hilarious to read, never foolish in observation yet endearing towards the fools. <br /><br />Mattie has <i>true grit</i> in every sense of the word, with the fire of her determination stoked by sheer will and courage. She soldiers on through rugged travel conditions and complains little. We are along for a fast and breath-stealing ride into hostile territory headlined by this dynamic, bickering trio of Mattie, Cogburn, and LaBoeuf, chock full of classic Western ambushes and gunfights. To hear a relatively dry retelling in Mattie’s distinctive voice is uniquely delightful and nerve-wracking. This man fires his rifle, that man dodges, those people are shot! Snakes! Skeletons! She will add in utter solemnity that a “scrap did not last as long as it has taken me to describe it.” Just in case you improperly over-excite yourself about a shootout experienced by a young girl, right? <br /><br />Portis’s <i>True Grit</i> is a true gem in literature, and I am so glad that my particular friend Julie brought this classic to my attention. There are few classics where I can say, plain and simple, that I had such unadulterated <i>fun</i>. No overwrought angst and a compelling story to tell—my goodness, what silliness has plagued young adults since then, Mattie would lament! </span>
